We need a report that simply lists what a user has worked on, and for how long in a (configurable) period of time.  This could be used to generate timesheets for employees.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5073].
  {panel}

When users want to configure permissions, they expect to find them on one page, not a few on 'Global permissions' and the rest in permission schemes.  Not knowing about global permissions is a common cause of support queries.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5072].
  {panel}

JIRA provides no safeguards against deleting groups like 'jira-users' or 'jira-administrators' when they are the only group granted the global 'Users' or 'Administrators' permission.  When no users have the 'Users' or 'Administrators' permissions, JIRA becomes pretty non-functional.  We check for this on the 'global permissions' page, but not when the group is being deleted.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-5047].
  {panel}

When reporting a issue against multiple versions it is often nice to have multiple issues which are then linked together (so each issue e.g. can be closed at seperate times). While this can be done manually, it would be really nice if JIRA gave me the option of doing this for me. So what JIRA should do in this case is to make several issues with the same title, and link these together.

It would furthermore be really nice if this could be done across projects.

